social_posts.post_text: My typical spin around tour of #38 all ready to ship out.  Walnut, Marroon canvas micarta spacer, and vintage Westinghouse cross cut canvas.  The blade is AEBL stainless and this customer wanted a shape for mainly carving and some daily carry tasks.  The blade profile is pretty much an “old school” sloyd knife.  Personally I think new school is all this “low belly” pointy stuff.  Yes it carves spoons really well, but it doesn’t do anything else super well.  The old school sloyd knife was a multi-tool.

Doing some reps today - I’ve been really quiet in the ‘grams this month.  I’ve been either working hard or dealing with family hardship.  Everyone has been sick, our pre-schooler brings it home and has honestly had it the worst this month.  Our lovely new dog is heading back to the fosters today, which really breaks my heart.  She scared my boy a couple times when she treated him like a rowdy puppy (which he is!) So she just isn’t a good fit for us right now, which sucks cause everything else about her is perfect.  Better to find her a better fit than create a fear of dogs in my son.  I love dogs, I need them in my life.

Super cool simple knife, but I have to admit I’ve been thinking a lot about how to bring these back to my more rustic roots of wood and metal.  It would have to be a different direction, as wood can’t handle the tight tolerance needed to make a safe and sturdy liner lock.  If I ponder it long enough something will come to me.  Once the idea forms I usually have to figure out I would execute it with the tooling I have.  I don’t have a mill and can’t afford one right now.  A ton of ideas I have fall down at “wish I had a mill”. Someday….

Small carving friction folders, and lots of other blades being prepped for heat treat.  These are NOT water-jet cut, which is starting to feel silly.  So much work cutting all those.  But I’m still not sure my designs are good enough to pay someone to reverse CAD them and then take on an inventory of blanks.  It takes me a really long time to decide my designs are good enough, like years, I constantly want to tweak little things.

Broken in Phosphor Bronze washers are very satisfying.  They feel hydraulic when properly adjusted and a little dirty.  This knife is dirty with pocket dust and lint, but the action is still really.  If I cleaned it out it would be quicker again, but I like the smooth slow action too.

Cranking up the speed today! 🤞  I waited too long to finally do this.  I started on a blinding fast grinder and then toned it down when I switched to the KMG.  But the addition of a second @beaumontmetalworks KMG variable speed let’s me crank this older one up for raw speed!!! It was scary before, now it’s terrifying.

I needed a bit of extra skin today.  My thumb pads get pretty cooked after a day of grinding, and it’s not what you think.  It’s not from touching the sand belt, it’s from hours of pushing on steel that is creeping up to 200-300 degrees F from friction.  It slowly just makes your skin so tender.  Half way through the day I wrapped them up and then the tap melts and I add more

All sorts of science and heat treating stuff going on this week, all week really.  No knives finished, just lots of processing.  The heap of blades to make pretty finished products from at the end should be impressive.

Asking for help is hard and awkward.  Talking about mental health is always hard and awkward.  Link in Bio, story below -

Hello followers and friends. Most of you know me as the guy that makes the weird curved knives. But I’m also self employed craftsman with Bipolar Disorder.  I didn’t realize exactly how much our furry friends can ground our mental health until my two senior dogs passed in 2022. In the last 3 months I have made two expensive efforts to replace my ESA - Emotional Support Animal. The first failed when our rescue pup, Margot scared my 3 year old son barking and growling at him. I spent a pretty penny on behavioral modification training and ultimately still couldn’t keep Margot, deciding that son’s life long love of dogs was more important than fitting this square dog into a round crate, so to speak. My second effort has now landed me a 9 week old Labrador puppy diagnosed with deadly Parvo virus 48 hours into my ownership. She has been dropped off at an inpatient vet and the $4000 deposit for base line treatment has been put on a credit card. Most of these financial decision on paper have not been my wisest, but that’s the trouble with mental health, people don’t always make the best decisions when looking for a way to feel better.  Small donations to help us pay that bill quickly will go a long way. Thanks for considering

Save Maeve - old video from day one, she is still hospitalized. 

Some people resort to really sad self destructive behaviors to cope with mental health struggles.  It’s really hard to help many of those people make better decisions, sometimes seemingly impossible.  I’m lucky, I just want a dog to take for quite walks and over a hundred people were willing to help me.  It won’t solve everything, therapy, meds and mindfulness play huge roles too (I stink at mindfulness) but my closest friends will confirm it helps a lot. 

After witnessing the power of this go fund me effort, I really hope I can make a regular effort to help ease another person’s troubled times.  It can be as simple as a phone call or a compliment, or big as setting up a go fund for someone else in need just so they can see that people do relate and do care. 

Thanks again everyone - link it bio, we’re so close to getting through this without much financial hardship.  At this point I can probably sell a few knives and we’ll be safe.  With lot of illnesses, dog or human, things can change any minute and cost can rise, so I’ll leave it active untill Maeve is prancing down the driveway again like this video

Update -  the good news for Maeve’s chances is we caught this early.  She is still doing very well on supportive care after 48 hours.  The bad news is we caught it early so the worst might be still yet to come.  Most dogs arrive in worse shape because the first 24-48 hours are tough to gauge if you dog is just having a bad day or if they are really sick.  We had the support of the entire network of people involved in this litter and the breeders attention and communication to gauge what was going on with these pups.  Another 48 hours should probably tell the whole story at an additional $1000-3000.  Maybe we’ll just sit tight for the weekend.  A lot of people rush it and bring the dog home early based on finances, only to end up back at the vet because things got worse again The emergency facility in Manchester NH has been pretty awesome in there clarity of billing, how they operate, and what to expect.  Because of how contagious Parvo is Maeve get’s her own nurse who doesnt interact with any other dogs on that shift.  It may seem expensive at first thought, but then you realize what goes into such care.

Thanks for all the support, would have been soooo hard without all of you.

Update and Thanks - I owe everyone a huge Thanks! and an update on Maeve the puppy.  She has made a full recovery, and shaping up to be a fantastic companion.  Our GoFundMe was successful beyond any expectations.  I’ve been chipping away at personal thank you, but I’m sure I’ll miss some. 

As for business updates - with all the well wish’s messages that came in last week, a lot of business messages got lost in the mix.  So ping me if I dropped the ball on business stuff.  The dog illness was not actually the top stresser of the last couple weeks.  The donations and the excellent vet care actually made that super easy, a little worry on the mind, but nothing too distracting.  The big time suck was sick kids and my wife going back to work.  I missed 11 days of work caring for my out of pre-school toddler.  My wife started a new job that same day my dog got sick, and I had both kids while making calls and trying to figure out where to bring my sick pup.  Illness ripped though all of us one by one over the next week.  I literally didn’t step foot in the shop for the entire time.  Anyway I’m through that one, and picked up where I left off the best I could.  All my focus is old work right now, and i am making a transition away from pre-paid orders.  I could go on forever on why, but I’ll just say I’m really disappoint in the way I managed my work this past year, and I’m determined to get back on track.  Untill the kids are older, I’m going to slow down a bit and make before I sell.  No more orders, pre-orders or customs in the near future.

Do you think the $100 hooks are all individually tested 🤷‍♂️. Well mine are.  They will show up perfect, from there it’s on you. 

My biggest failure in QC happened a few years ago when I put too much faith in a high performance hot bond glue in combo with the round tangs.  Big failure, and it bit me.  I had a lot of hook rotating in the handles.  Not all, but plenty of them, and I felt terrible.  Over a year ago I switched to key way style tangs to reduce chance of bond breaking rotation and I use a more tradition single part slow cure metal/wood glue.

Still some room for improvement that I’ll get to some day.  But I dunked this w2 in vinegar for a few hours yesterday to reveal an “auto-hamon” which is essentially a reveal of differential hardening that happens without intention.  You can control this outcome with clay but this time it just happened naturally.  The dark sections are soft steel, if done intentionally you would cover the spin with a special clay to increase the durability of the blade, and you can play with the clay shape a bit just for fun and esthetics.  Thanks to @jwbladeworks for chat to understand this process better, check out his hamon work to see what a truely proper hamon can be

Interested in steels outside the realm of the traditional greenwood / wood working scene?  I am!  I’ve been working with two steels for past 6-8 months to determine if they are a good fit for our little niche tools.  The blade to the left is CPM3V a tough high alloy tool steel with a significant Vanadium addition.  Vanadium provides super hard carbides within the steel structure to slow abrasion wear at the edge.  It’s definitely slower to sharpen, and I suggest you only take interest if your sharpening skills are on point.  Only silicon carbide papers or diamonds are hard enough to cut vanadium alloyed blades.  This particular steel is also rated one of the toughest out there.  Without getting too into the technical weeds it balances a moderate carbon content with the additional alloying to balance the overall HRC with added abrasion resistance.  A simple carbon steel blade at a brittle 64hrc will still wear faster and feel softer at the sharpening stone than a 3V at 60hrc. 

The blade to the right is AEB-L a classic stainless designed for the razor blade industry.  This steel has a wonderful balance for a carving knife.  Chromium carbides (harder than carbon alone) in fine distribution boost the wear resistance over simpler carbon steels like 52100, 1095 and O1.  It is noticeable easier to sharpen than the 3V, I don’t notice a huge difference in effort than to carbon steel and no more rust.

My heat treating on these steels include is oxygen reduction in kiln controlled heats and liquid nitrogen cryogenic post processes.
Back to a shape that really got things kicked off.  Doesn’t get much better than roasted curly Birds Eye maple.

Sharing a clip from a few weeks ago.  AEBL liquid nitrogen cryo problem solving - AEBL really likes to warp in cryo.  I really blew it a few months back when I went ahead and dunked $4k worth of AEBL folder blades into the dewar and pulled out a bunch of useless trash. 

I figured I should clamp them to keep them straight, but the hole in the top of dewar is only about 2” so I didn’t have an idea on how yet.  And I winged it.  Well you only make that mistake once! 

I fashioned these custom clamps that can take up to 6 blades and still fit through the opening on the dewar.  It worked great and I have to say Liquid Nitrogen brings AEBL alive as other people have said.  I can now hit the top of the hardness range for one of the toughest stainless steels made. 

Now I understand why I should have bought a wide mouth dewar 😤

Wood doesn’t have to be crazy exotic to be awesome.  When I first started making knives I decided to only use woods that were natural to my area.  It felt like a nice creative restraint to just grabbing for that curly Koa wood every time.  And while curly maple is certainly a crowd favorite, my favorite knives are always those pieces of unexpected beauty.  This is Mulberry, often a bit of a weed tree that pops up in suburban areas left to grow up, or planted ornaments.  It doesn’t often exist in a nature forest in this area, but this tree did.  It was harvested by a logging company assuming it was oak, they didn’t really care anyway.  It was over 24 inches at the base.  One of the employees at the mill noticed a leaf on the bare trunk and snatched it up to mill for himself.  He sold me a few boards cheap.  It’s made some wonderful knives.

🎉🎉🎉 that is the rest of the hooks owed to customers plus a bunch of extras.  The extras will be the first hooks available for sale in nearly a year.  They will go on the website as they are finished a few at a time. 

Here they are heat treated and tempered and ready to bevel and finish.  The grinding and finishing is the slowest part of the whole process, and the part that takes the most metal focus.  It often leads to a slightly shortened work day, because my neck and eyes are pretty tired from tension.  I really enjoy the few days spent forging and heat treating a batch like this.  It’s fun to see the pile growing and it’s easy task to find “flow” in.  I’ve slowly learned to relax in the forging process and just let the piece take form and be what it is.  I used to spend way to much time stressing over making exact copies of the last one.  For all there little quirks and differences they are always fine in the end, and if they are truely weird I just sell them to @bgancsos for the Matt White museum of oddities.

Open curve hook knives - got two available on my website right now.
People often call them finishing hooks.  Personally I believe it’s much easier to pick one hook that guides the desired shape and start and finish with that hook.  Alternatively I believe one of the most valuable benefits of an open curve knife is to let it be a teaching tool.  I’ve seen countless “first spoons” or early spoons that I call “scoops on a stick”. The new carver will often have a tendency to over hollow in the beginning.  They are typically using a Mora with a tight curve that lets them dig as deep as they want and with that achieving a smooth finish gets harder and harder the deeper they go.  While it’s certainly not the only use for an open curve, using it as to teaching tool to see that spoons don’t really need that much of bowl to be very functional is pretty eye opening.  The open curve will effectively stop you from over hollowing.  It will tell you when you’re done, from there you can dial in the finish without the back and fourth of digging and gouging and then trying again and again to smooth

Sometimes I’ll make a little one off hook just to scratch an itch.  Personally I always just come back to my standard Monadnock curve but I understand some people like other things.  If the initial forging starts to look a little different I may lay into that and free hand it a bit.  This knife is available on my website.  I’ll call it “open compound”. It Covers a lot of the similar range of my Monadnock, but stretched out a little at the open portion and just barely tightened up at the tip.  I’ve always found it doesn’t take much to be noticable in function, even just an 1/8” diameter change to your bending mandrel can open a door to doing something different with your spoons.  If you like it, that’s cool, you may see more you may not 😉

I’m thrilled with how these wood/micarta friction folders came out.  These are small knives for a reason.  Having no lock, it’s important that your fingers refrain from pushing on the back of the blade.  It won’t snap shut or anything if you forget, but it’s awkward feeling.  The small blade let’s your adjust your off hand thumb from the blade to the tip of the handle.  It’s an easy adjustment actually and it feels pretty natural.  You may also be surprised how often you “back drag” your carving knife, meaning you make your cut and bring the knife back for the next cut without actually removing it from the wood.  This was very noticeable when I tested a few larger friction folders, as the longer blade had more leverage during said back drag to move the blade.  With the small knife it’s easy to find a pivot adjust where the knife is quite solid.  It’s too small to carve all day with, but it’s a fun piece to pull out for a quick session.
😍😍. New material and I love it.  Any guesses?  Back spacer is jade G10 and the blade is 52100 on this one.  #frictionfolder #handmadefolder #handmadefoldingknife

First locking folder in quite some time.  This took me way to long to get through, but I was admittedly not in tune with the process and order of operations.  The next one i might be able to make better than minimum wage on 🤦🏼‍♂️. Few updates.  The wood is shifted to the Non lock bar side and bonded to a stainless liner.  The lock bar side HAS to be synthetic on these, as there is no good way that I want to work through the order of operations with the wood bonded to the lock bar side.  The early versions of the carving folders where reported to be a bit to bulky.  The next iteration was perhaps a bit to scant and loss some rigidity.  This iteration using the dual liners brings the weight up again, but it’s still not as bulky as the first 10 or so.  I’m getting up to around serial #40 I think, I have to check my notes.  This one Is cherry roasted, jade g10 and black Rich Lite.  #linerlock #sloydknife

A cherry/Micarta friction folder in process, and some other eye candies.  The profile is tuned in first to match the proportions of the blade as best I can.  These blade are hand made, not lazer cut, so slight variations can occur and the handle is the spot where I can make a compensation for esthetics if needed.  Next I’ll profile and finish.  The faces get domed, and then some final chamfers to soften the hardest edges.
Serial Number FF019. (19th friction folder) ready to head out #frictionfolder #sloydknife

These axes are sooo nice, but man I’ve seen some with downright unusable grinds from GB.  Obnoxiously convex to where I found the axe glanced so often it was exhausting to use.  No glancing here, and super easy to re-sharpen. 

Honestly I understand why they grind them the way they do. These are roughly $300 axes, and they are hand made.  There is a lot of work that needs to be done for that $300.  I would charge WAY more.

Here is a sibling to the last one.  Tried an acid etch on the D2 and it worked out.  I’ve definitely botched things in the etching stage before. 

This one is definitely going to be a regular offering.

Third attempt at a pattern to reduce weight on the folding knife liners.  Old pattern right side, new Left side.  Mapping out a pattern like that by eye is tricky.  My brain doesn’t do math easily and computers are evil so I can’t cad.  I don’t have the patience.  I want my hands on the piece and I want it taking shape in front of me asap.  But I also want the spaces between the weight relief holes to be fairly consistent so there is a sense and flow to the entire thing. 

Why do I care about an artistic detail on part of the build that the customer never sees 🤦🏼‍♂️ Because I have to look at it for weeks before it comes together as a complete knife and I’m mentally ill.

I like very subtle lines and transitions in my designs.  There is a typical evolution for me where the design continues to “mellow out” through the first few attempts.  To the left is the tracing template that I arrived at after the first few sketches of a concept.  Middle is second time I implemented that shape in a finished knife and the maroon to the right is the 4th time I finished the shape.  Each time the features mellow out while proportionally staying the same and I like the knife more and more.

Something a bit different - my typical sloyd knife has gotten really “spoony” lately.  The low belly edge profiles and fine tip frenzy have taken over. 80CrV2 - .110 thickness, no bevel, just prepped for destruction testing.  Rapid DET anneal (1400° vermiculite cool), 1525° 10 minute soak austenized, Parks50 quench, -25°C “Cryo”, 380° temper for 4 hours.  It’s tough, that’s for sure.  Other samples have held an edge well.  Sorry no HRC determined.  The only difference in a true model would be the pregrind bevel which I guess makes the quench at the edge faster.  I wonder if there is any change from the one variable 🤷‍♂️. Thanks to @knifesteelnerds for taking the time to do an article clarifying some of the misnomers about this steel.

How do you all keep your carbon tools from rusting?  Have you learned hard lessons?  I made a mistake of leaving this new blade out on the bench over the weekend, and the side that was up must have caught some condensation and now has to be refinished.  Bummer.  When I’m paying attention I make sure that everything is under cover when I leave it.  So I either place a sheet of cardboard over the tray of in process knives, or I put the entire tray into a drawer.  I find that drawers work best, I think because it slows down that environment change that causes condensation and then rust.  New England is brutal about 40-50° temp swings and depending on the humidity that can make a real mess in my shop.  Everything rusts!  What do you all do?

AEBL stainless oil quenched with cryo.  Beautifully clean oxide finish, finely distributed chromium carbides to resist wear.  Longer edge life than anything low alloy, and barely harder to sharpen than the stuff wood crafters are used to.  Low Alloy Carbon steels like the typical O1 and 10xx get their resistance to abrasive wear (think silica in wood) from carbon carbides which are the softest of the typical carbides found in tool/knife steels. “High alloys” some of which are stainless, have significant additions of typically Chromium and Vanadium which are harder (vanadium the highest) and more resistant to wear.  That’s where the old adage “harder to sharpen” comes from.  You have little particles in there that are harder to cut.  It doesn’t mean the HRC, a scale we use to determine the hardness of steel has to go up.  There is space between the carbides that averages out the overall HRC.  3V steel with lots of vanadium is harder to sharpen than 1095 even when the HRC of 1095 is higher.  I love AEBL because it’s well balanced.  It’s super strong (lots more to say on toughness in another post) while having just enough chromium carbide to help the edge last longer.  Bonus it’s resists rusting very well.  It is important to know that by leaving the oxide finish on the flats I’m reducing it’s corrosion resistance a bit on the flats.  In this style of tool I’m not worried about that.  I know everyone likes the black oxide and these tools are generally well cared for.  The bevel will have the high corrosion resistance stainless is known for.  AEBL isn’t the highest, but the really high rated resistant steels are not appropriate for this style of tool.  There is no ultimate steel, only a steel that’s well suited to it’s intended use.  Wow that was super technical.  Let’s go back and just look at that cherry wood again. 😳

Rough draft of something I really need to get right.  I do a lot of birch bark sheaths, but the resource of satisfactory bark isn’t always the easiest.  You have harvest it at the right time, and you should have permission to do so, or be harvesting from fleshly cut trees.  Often the bark isn’t up to my standards.  I like a thick leather like pliable bark that doesn’t delaminate on its own.  All that to say it would be nice to have an alternative.  I also see leather work as a higher end finished  product when done properly.  This is not super well done, but it proved out some ideas.  It’s welted, kydex lined and fits the way I want it to.  The kydex lining, while not traditional by any means helps the pointy tipped knife not catch and ruin the sheath.  Wood can do the same thing, but it so often rusts the blades, and I’m not into that.  Next try needs a saddle stitch and better leather.

Here is a moment of the process of sharpening the hook knife and some in-site as to how I intend you to do it.  The railed system is beautiful because it’s quick and offers a built in guide.  My left is holding the knife loosely so that it can float on the dowel.  Don’t try to clamp down, then your dowel hand will have to hold an angle, just let it ride and it finds the angle for you.  I don’t bother with sticky back paper as it’s too slow for me and I’ve mastered a technique without it.  You might find it helps to secure the paper to the dowel to have one less moving variable, that’s fine.  I use fairly stiff papers so I can push stroke and they don’t crumple up.  After a progression of papers up to 5000 it’s stropping to finish.  Where do I start?  Well I start at 320 because I’m forming an edge from nothing.  I suggest the user start are fine as they can that will efficiently raise a burr.  That’s usually roughly 1000 grit on the average tool.  Excessive use of 400 grit will take its toll on your tool, so avoid it if possible.  If you had rough damage, such as you get from dropping a tool or hitting metals you might have to go that low to be efficient, it really takes feeling it out.  You need to know what you’re looking for, and that’s to get back through any damaged edge and back to “zero” thickness, usually we call that the burr.

AEBL is a wonderful steel.  It’s a happy medium between the old faithful carbon steels and new super steel compositions.  It rates and tests out to be both tougher and more abrasion resistant than almost anything in blacksmiths realm of carbon steels.  No tricky ultra hard vanadium to deal with, it sharpens like carbon steel.  It’s been proven to have some of the best micro structure outside of Powder Metallurgy steels.  That fine “grain” is part of what lets it get so sharp and helps keep the edge from degrading quickly.
